entries.title: Hundreds Gather to Memorialize Renowned African Human Rights Lawyer
entries.description: Thulani Maseko, who had pushed for years to end Africa’s last absolute monarchy, in Eswatini, formerly Swaziland, was killed in front of his wife and two young children.

entries.title: Czech Republic Elects Petr Pavel President Over Andrej Babis
entries.description: Petr Pavel, a political novice, defeated Andrej Babis, a populist business tycoon and former prime minister, in the first of several important European elections this year.

entries.title: Amid Spasm of Violence, Israel’s Far-Right Government Raises Risk of Escalation
entries.description: Israel and the West Bank were gripped by violence this week. Its roots predate Israel’s new far-right government, but the government’s ministers and goals are fueling tensions.

entries.title: British Airline, Flybe, Collapses a Second Time
entries.description: Flybe, once the largest independent regional airline in Europe, canceled all flights on Saturday. A new owner failed to save the carrier, which was already struggling when the pandemic hit.

entries.title: Fighting Rages in Eastern Ukraine Over Critical Supply Routes
entries.description: While the heaviest fighting is still around the city of Bakhmut, in recent days Russian forces have stepped up assaults on a strategic town farther to the south.

entries.title: Tiny Radioactive Capsule Missing in Australia
entries.description: The device, part of a sensor used in mining, is believed to have fallen off the back of a truck while in transit.

entries.title: The Gin Boom Trying to Change India, One Distillery at a Time
entries.description: Local concoctions are challenging the country’s conservative attitude toward alcohol, along with the country’s often stultifying bureaucracy.

entries.title: 2 Injured in Jerusalem Attack, Hours After a Nearby Mass Shooting
entries.description: Two Israelis were shot and injured on Saturday in East Jerusalem, the day after an attack outside a synagogue elsewhere in the city killed seven people.

entries.title: Police Beating in Memphis
entries.description: Americans once again protested after another recorded instance of police brutality.

entries.title: What Happened to Canada’s Cold War Relics?
entries.description: Few of the sites built to protect Canadians from a radioactive cloud of destruction have been preserved.

entries.title: Kharkiv Got Some Breathing Space, but Still Doesn’t Breathe Easily
entries.description: For the past four months, residents have slowly trickled back into the reclaimed city. But signs of the conflict — and the chance that it might return — are everywhere.

entries.title: To Fix Its Problems in Ukraine, Russia Turns to the Architect of the War
entries.description: President Vladimir V. Putin is on his third overall commander in Ukraine. But his military’s fundamental issues have not been addressed, Western officials say.

entries.title: Move Over, Pablo Neruda. Young Chileans Have a New Favorite Poet.
entries.description: Gabriela Mistral, the first Latin American to win a Nobel Prize for literature, was long considered staid. A new generation is reclaiming her as an anti-establishment icon.

entries.title: New Zealand’s Largest City Grapples With Aftermath of Devastating Floods
entries.description: At least two people were killed in the flooding in Auckland that forced hundreds of people from their homes and shut down the city’s airport, which was submerged.

entries.title: Russia Outlaws a News Site and a Rights Group, Stifling Critical Voices
entries.description: The Kremlin stepped up efforts to banish independent sources of news. Prosecutors labeled Meduza, a popular news site, “undesirable,” so anyone who aids or promotes it can be prosecuted.
